{
  "texts": [
    "Integrally, Yoshida [Yos87, §3.5] also requires the existences of certain coequalisers in C. This discrepancy amounts to the fact that integrally it is not enough for the Burnside homomorphism to be injective, but rather we also require the image to be closed under multiplication.The strength in the rational Burnside ring is that the isomorphism of Theorem 2.4 allows us to identify idempotents through the process of Möbius inversion, i.e., by inverting the hom-set matrix.Lemma 2.6 ([Yos87, Lemma 5.4]).",
    "Let C be a finite skeletal category.",
    "If C has an epi-mono factorization system, then the idempotent 𝑒 𝑑 of 𝐴 Q (C) corresponding to 𝑑 ∈ C is given by𝑒 𝑑 = ∑︁ 𝑐∈C (𝐻 -1) 𝑐𝑑 𝑐,where 𝐻 is the hom-set matrix.The abstract Burnside ring of Yoshida recovers the classical Burnside ring for a finite group 𝐺, see [Yos87, Example 3.3.(a)].",
    "We will illustrate that on a simple example.Example 2.7.",
    "Let C be the orbit category of the 𝐶 6, the cyclic group of order 6."
  ]
}